Open Access¶

Open Access refers to publications which are available without restrictions such as subscription fees.Currently there is no consensus on the impact of open access status on citation count: several studies report a positive correlation between the two, particularly for "gold" open access, while others question these findings and suggest that no relationship is present.

In [53]:
Image("./openaccess.png")
Out[53]:

Approximately 37 % of the articles in the data set were marked as Open Access.

Every paper had associated to it a value to describe the number of academic fields it covered, and it serves as a measure of multidisciplinarity.

Included in the data set were the titles of the articles, stripped of punctuation. The literature available on the relationship between article title and citations suggests that shorter titles correlate with higher citation counts. A new feature, title length, was therefore extracted from the title.

Altmetric Availability¶

Of all the articles in the data set, less than 30 % had at least one altmetric associated to them, while for the rest no altmetrics data was available.

In [67]:
plt.figure(figsize=(7,7))

no = len(df) - len(df.mendeley.dropna())
percentyes = round(yes/(yes+no)*100,1)
percentno = 100-percentyes
plt.pie([yes, no],
        labels=["Altmetrics Available\n %s " % percentyes + "%",
                "Altmetrics Not Available\n %s " % percentno + "%"])
plt.title("Altmetrics Availability")
plt.show()

With such a high fraction of unavailable data, standard techniques for handling missing data cannot be applied. Furthermore, the distribution of the missing data does not appear to be random: the two groups appear to be noticeably different, as can be observed in the two histograms below.

Altmetric Distribution¶

The most common altmetric is Mendeley, with 2080 non-null values, followed by Twitter with 1942. All other altmetrics had less than 500 mentions.

Based on these observations, and considering that to include other altmetrics would require reducing the size of the data set even further, it was decided to keep Mendeley as the only altmetric to be used in the model. Missing values were set to zero and, to preserve the information on the missing article a new binary feature was introduced to mark articles which were missing Mendeley data.

Model Selection and Evaluation¶

Six different algorithms were tried:

  • Random Forests
  • K-Nearest Neighbors
  • Neural Network
  • Support Vector Machines (Linear, RBF, Polynomial)
In [386]:
df["missing"] = [1 if i == True else 0 for i in df.mendeley.isnull()]
imputed = df.fillna(0)
imputed["authors"] = np.log(imputed.authors)
imputed["mendeley"] = np.cbrt(imputed.mendeley)
In [446]:
mms = MinMaxScaler()
ss = StandardScaler()

lr = LinearSVR()
knn = KNeighborsRegressor(weights="distance", n_neighbors=5)
rf = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=50)
svr = SVR(kernel="poly")
svrrbf = SVR(kernel="rbf")
nn = MLPRegressor(hidden_layer_sizes=(72,36),activation="relu",learning_rate="adaptive",max_iter=1000)

def score(transformer, estimator): 
    pipe = Pipeline([('transformer', transformer), ('estimator', estimator)])
    cv = KFold(n_splits=10)
    return(cross_val_score(pipe,
                           imputed[["authors","fields","year","oa","mendeley","missing"]],
                           imputed["citations"], 
                           cv=cv))
In [410]:
scknn = score(ss, knn)
scrf = cross_val_score(RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=50),
                       imputed[["authors","fields","year","oa","mendeley","missing"]],
                       imputed["citations"], 
                       cv = KFold(n_splits=10))
sclr = score(ss, LinearSVR())
scsvr = score(ss, svr)
scnn = score(mms, nn)
svrrbf = SVR(kernel="rbf")

The best performing algorithm was SVM with polynomial kernel, with a median R2 score of 0.39.

During testing, it was observed that the information on title length decreased the performance of the algorithms, and it was therefore dropped. By analysing the training and test sets used to calculate the scores, it was found that higher scores were recorded when the mean citation count was similar in both training and test sets, and vice versa: this is a sign that the model is struggling to generalize the problem, likely due to insufficient data.

After hyperparameter optimization, the median R2 was further increased to 0.43. As a final test, the model was then used to predict the total number of citations for papers published in 2015, based on the data from 2016 and 2017.

Final Comments¶

A machine learning model can only be as good as the data that it learns from. The model described is a good starting point, but by improving the quality of the data, we can aim for much more reliable predictions. This can be done in several ways:

  • Including author information: it is a well known fact that some authors attract more citations than others for a number of reasons (skill, reputation, networking...). Adding the main author's H-Index would likely help to train a better model.
  • Including impact factor: an article published on Nature will likely attract more attention than one published on a low-impact factor journal.
  • Including field information: some fields of research generate more citations than others.
  • Collecting data at regular time intervals. The data set used in this investigation provided a snapshot of the citation counts and altmetrics at a given point in time. By following the time evolution of these metrics, we can provide valuable information to the algorithm, e.g. knowing how many citations a certain article had after six months, one year, two years...
  • Understanding why so many data points are missing for altmetrics.
